Safeguard for #message existence: checked if (msg) { ... } else { console.warn(...) }.
Added a small inline-style fallback for debugging:
msg.style.transition = 'opacity 0.6s ease' (if not set) and msg.style.opacity = '1' immediately after adding .show.
After 2s we remove the class and set msg.style.opacity = '0'.
Rationale: if some CSS rule was still preventing the .show opacity change, setting inline opacity forces the element visible while we debug.
Why that fixed it

The message element was correctly updated by JS but remained visually hidden because of CSS issues (missing color, duplicated/overridden rules, or stacking order). The combination of explicit color, removing duplicates, setting z-index, and the inline opacity fallback ensured the DOM text change became visible.
